# Trino Best Practices

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use Proper Naming Conventions
Acronyms in naming should follow title casing. This improves readability and maintains consistency across the codebase.

❌ BAD
```java
HttpClient client = new HttpClient();
```

✅ GOOD
```java
HttpClient client = new HttpClient();
```

### Organize Code by Functionality
Group related classes and functions together. This makes the codebase easier to navigate and maintain.

❌ BAD
```
src/
  ├── utils/
  ├── models/
  ├── services/
  └── controllers/
```

✅ GOOD
```
src/
  ├── user/
  │   ├── UserService.java
  │   └── UserController.java
  ├── order/
  │   ├── OrderService.java
  │   └── OrderController.java
  └── utils/
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Avoid SELECT *
Using `SELECT *` can lead to unnecessary data retrieval, which increases I/O and degrades performance. Always specify the columns you need.

❌ BAD
```sql
SELECT * FROM orders;
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
SELECT order_id, customer_id, total_amount FROM orders;
```

### Optimize Joins with Smaller Tables First
When joining tables, ensure the smaller table is on the build (right) side of the join to optimize memory usage.

❌ BAD
```sql
SELECT *
FROM large_table lt
JOIN small_table st ON lt.id = st.large_table_id;
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
SELECT *
FROM small_table st
JOIN large_table lt ON lt.id = st.large_table_id;
```

## Performance Considerations

### Maintain Up-to-Date Table Statistics
Regularly run the `ANALYZE` command to keep table statistics current. This helps the Cost-Based Optimizer (CBO) generate efficient execution plans.

❌ BAD
```sql
-- Forgetting to analyze tables
SELECT * FROM orders WHERE order_date > '2023-01-01';
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
ANALYZE orders;
SELECT * FROM orders WHERE order_date > '2023-01-01';
```

### Use Dynamic Filtering
When joining large fact tables to small dimension tables, leverage dynamic filtering to push down predicates and skip unnecessary data.

❌ BAD
```sql
SELECT *
FROM large_fact_table lft
JOIN small_dimension_table sdt ON lft.dim_id = sdt.id
WHERE sdt.category = 'electronics';
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
SELECT *
FROM large_fact_table lft
JOIN small_dimension_table sdt ON lft.dim_id = sdt.id
WHERE sdt.category = 'electronics' 
  AND lft.order_date > '2023-01-01';
```

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Avoid Mutable Collections
Use immutable collections to prevent unintended side effects and improve code clarity.

❌ BAD
```java
List<String> names = new ArrayList<>();
names.add("Alice");
names.add("Bob");
```

✅ GOOD
```java
List<String> names = List.of("Alice", "Bob");
```

### Follow Effective Java Guidelines
Adhere strictly to Effective Java guidelines for better code quality and maintainability.

❌ BAD
```java
CompletableFuture<String> future = new CompletableFuture<>();
```

✅ GOOD
```java
ListenableFuture<String> future = Futures.immediateFuture("result");
```

## Testing Approaches

### Use Unit Tests for Critical Logic
Ensure that all critical business logic is covered with unit tests. This helps catch issues early and ensures code reliability.

❌ BAD
```java
// No unit tests for business logic
public void processOrder(Order order) {
    // processing logic
}
```

✅ GOOD
```java
@Test
public void testProcessOrder() {
    Order order = new Order();
    // setup order
    processOrder(order);
    // assert expected outcomes
}
```

### Integration Tests for SQL Queries
Implement integration tests to validate SQL queries against the database. This ensures that queries perform as expected in a real environment.

❌ BAD
```java
// No integration tests for SQL queries
public void fetchOrders() {
    // SQL query logic
}
```

✅ GOOD
```java
@Test
public void testFetchOrders() {
    List<Order> orders = fetchOrders();
    assertFalse(orders.isEmpty());
}
```

## Conclusion
By following these best practices, you will ensure that your Trino development is efficient, maintainable, and high-performing. Always prioritize performance in your SQL queries and adhere to effective coding standards in Java.